<script>
	var comments={
			1360: {
				id_comment: 1360,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "Literally, ‘the pen of a man’. This has often been translated ‘with an ordinary pen’ or ‘in the common speech of the country’, but it is difficult to see why either direction should be necessary. In Deut. 3.11 ‘the cubit of a man’ is evidently a measurement taken from the arm of an ordinary man, not from that of a giant."
			},
					1361: {
				id_comment: 1361,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "The people of Juda are blamed for cutting themselves off from the holy city (here represented by the pool of Siloe, its water-supply), and permitting the son of Romelia to enter their country (II Par. 28.6). They will be punished by a flood, that is, the invasion of Juda by Sennacherib (IV Kg. 18); it will drown them only up to the neck, because Jerusalem will remain unconquered."
			},
					1362: {
				id_comment: 1362,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "vv. 9, 10. These verses are evidently addressed to the defeated forces of Sennacherib."
			},
					1363: {
				id_comment: 1363,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "The Latin (though not the Hebrew text) would also yield the sense ‘it is rather the (alarmist) language of these people themselves that should be accounted treason’."
			},
					1364: {
				id_comment: 1364,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "It is commonly assumed that Almighty God himself will be a stone, a boulder, etc; but the sense of this is not evident, and there is no reason, either in the Latin or in the Hebrew, why the subject of the verb should not be neuter. This national crisis will be a means of sanctification to Isaias and his disciples; others, taken unawares by it, will involve themselves in ruin (e.g., by taking flight and falling into the hands of the Assyrians)."
			},
					1365: {
				id_comment: 1365,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "The word ‘children’ may be taken literally (cf. 7.3 and 8.3 above); St Jerome, however, understands it of the prophet’s disciples."
			},
					1366: {
				id_comment: 1366,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "Literally, ‘he will go through it’ (the land). Verses 21, 22 probably relate to the position of Sennacherib after his defeat (IV Kg. 19.35), the prophet’s thought having gone back to verse 8 above. The invasion is there described as a spreading out of wings, and here, in verse 22, Sennacherib is warned that he will not be able to ‘fly away’ from his calamity."
			},
			};
</script>
